data.name: House at Pooh Corner by Kenny Loggins
data.description:
House at Pooh Corner was written by a teenage Kenny Loggins as he was getting ready to graduate from High School. Composed as an ode to lost innocence, as he prepared to leave his childhood behind, Kenny remembered the first book he’d ever read, A.A. Milne’s 1928 novel of short stories, “The House at Pooh Corner.”  

As Kenny identified Christopher Robin leaving the hundred acre wood with his own experience “House At Pooh Corner” was born.

data.name: I'm Yours by Jason Mraz
data.description: Jason Mraz shares the spiritual story behind his multi-generational, Grammy-nominated hit single "I'm Yours." Released in 2008, "I'm Yours" is one of Mraz's biggest hits to date, spending an impressive 76 weeks on the Hot 100, and claiming a spot as one of the top selling digital singles of all time.

data.name: Heart and Soul by Huey Lewis
data.description: The back story on Huey’s 1983 top 10 smash hit "Heart and Soul" from the number one album “SPORTS." Learn how the different melodies came together as they recorded this last song with the intention of writing a hit for the album.

data.name: Power Of Love by Huey Lewis
data.description: Get the story behind the number one smash from the 1985 blockbuster “Back to the Future."  Discussed in detail with Huey, he elaborates on his role in the film and how the song gave the band their first No.1 hit on the US Billboard Hot 100.

data.name: Feel It Still by Portugal. The Man
data.description: Just released in the spring of 2017, "Feel It Still" quickly became one of the biggest chart cross-overs of the 2010s, hitting No. 1 on the US Alternative Charts and peaking at No. 4 on the Billboard Hot 100 by fall of the same year. Check out the in-depth commentary with Portugal. The Man on their magnetic single "Feel It Still."

data.name: God Only Knows by The Beach Boys
data.description: Musical genius Brian Wilson and Lyricst Tony Asher share the thought process behind one of American pop’s greatest compositions,  as well as Paul McCartney’s favorite song of all time, "God Only Knows." Released in 1966, the song's lyrics reflects on moving forward after loss and god being addressed as any higher force outside ourselves.
